column1: How many of the following teams will not qualify for the 2018 FIFA World Cup's Round of 16: Argentina, Belgium, Brazil, England, France, Germany, Portugal, Russia, Spain, and Switzerland?
column6: ['Sports']
column11: "The 2018 FIFA World Cup starts with the group stage, and the top two teams from each group qualify for the Round of 16. For more information about the World Cup and its matches, please visit FIFA. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: Germany
Welp, that was not the result I expected for Germany!
It's over, Germany is the only one out, the only team I gave near certainty for entering the final stage.
Suspect Germany will not make it to the round of 16.
Feeling

It's all over for Germany. They have always been a good bet to reach semifinals at least, but here they were decisively beaten by lowly South Korea (but let's not forget the latter reached the semi-final as co-host).
Germany.
Model update
Croatia replaced the starting goalkeeper, 4 defence men, and others, Iceland failed to take advantage.

Updated for latest results. Only Brazil, Germany and Switzerland are not yet through but have probabilities of 89%, 87% and 96% per five thirty eight as of 6.26.2018: https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2018-world-cup-predictions/
Just Germany, Brazil and Switzerland remaining out of these ten. There is a small probability for "2" using 538, but I'm ignoring that.
Just Germany, Brazil and Switzerland remaining out of these ten. "0" should be 75% using 538's current probabilities, but I'm going to go with my biases here.
Impossible for BOTH Brazil and Switzerland to miss out.

Country: [my updated forecast] vs. [538 on Saturday 12pm CET [1]] Argentina: 50% vs. 48% Belgium: 100% Brazil: 90% vs. 89% England: 100% France: 100% Germany: 83% vs. 87% Portugal: 100% Russia: 100% Spain: 100% Switzerland: 95% vs. 96% In expectation I have 0.82 teams not making it vs. 538 having 0.8 teams not making it. I update in my previous prediction based on feeling in direction of my prediction, i.e. more probability mass for 0 or 1 team.
Slight tweak reflecting Portugal having qualified. Probabilities will change dramatically tomorrow - one way or another - after the Argentina Nigeria match tonight.
Model update. In order of likeliness to progress: Belgium, England, France, Portugal, Russia, Spain (100%) Switzerland (99%) Brazil (92%) Germany (84%) Argentina (56%)
Big change since yesterday is Portugal securing their place in the next round.
Model update. In order of likeliness to progress: Belgium, England, France, Russia (100%) Spain (99%) Switzerland (98%) Brazil (92%) Portugal (87%) Germany (83%) Argentina (56%)

After Argentina vs Nigeria tomorrow there will be big changes in the probabilities above. A Nigerian win would practically remove the option for "0" - unless Iran beat Portugal today, Conversely an Argentine win, barring a freak result for Iceland over Croatia, would increase "0" to about 65%.
England Belgium Russia Uruguay Croatia are safe. But the rest are are up in the air. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_FIFA_World_Cup#Round_of_16

If the math is right, Germany only needs to win by 2 goals over SK to ensure a place in the next round. A win gives them 6 points, Sweden needs a win over Mexico to reach 6 points. Fortunately for Germany, a Mex. loss leaves them with a goal differential that is no higher than +1. A 2 goal win for Germany ensures at least a second place finish.
Germany pulls their odds up with a last minute win over Sweden.

With two rounds of the group matches complete, the only one of these teams still looking vulnerable is Argentina. There would need to be some possible though less likely results (such as Serbia beating Brazil, or Sweden beating Mexico) for other teams not to reach the last 16.

Country: [my updated forecast] vs. [538 on Saturday 12pm CET [1]] Argentina: 50% vs. 48% Belgium: 90% vs. 96% Brazil: 95% vs. 89% England: 90% vs. 96% France: 100% Germany: 80% vs. 64% Portugal: 95% vs. 86% Russia: 100% Spain: 95% vs. 99% Switzerland: 95% vs. 96% In expectation I have 1.1 teams not making it vs. 538 having 1.26 teams not making it. I update in my previous prediction based on intuition in direction of my prediction.
Moving "zero" from 8 to 24 after the latest round of games. By first drawing with Brazil and now beating Serbia, the Swiss have exceeded my expectations, and are looking safe.
Big movers today: * Switzerland now a near certainty * Argentina's odds up a bit after Nigeria did them a solid against Iceland.

Model update. Argentina's result has shifted this. In order of likeliness to progress: France (100%) Russia (100%) Spain (99%) England (94%) Belgium (93%) Portugal (87%) Brazil (86%) Switzerland (67%) Germany (60%) Argentina (37%)

Argentina is in most danger - they'll be knocked out if Iceland beat Nigeria today. Switzerland have a crucial match against Serbia - they could be in trouble if they lose. There's even an outside chance that Germany could be the third team not to qualify if they don't beat Sweden (who knocked out Italy to get to this stage).
Big ouch for Argentina.
Qualitative adjustment for the chance of Germany on top of 538 that I might regret.
Argentina's lower chances of qualifying.
I skimmed over the results of the passed 2 days, looks good for all teams so far.
Model update. In order of likeliness to progress: Russia (100%) Spain (99%) Belgium (95%) England (94%) France (87%) Portugal (87%) Brazil (85%) Argentina (74%) Switzerland (66%) Germany (61%)

Russia qualified, Spain almost so, Portugal just have to avoid defeat against Iran. Next up are matches involving France and Argentina - the latter dropped two points against Iceland and will have to do better against Croatia now.
Who knew the home ground advatange would be so big? It's worth half a goal usually but seems to have given the Russkis a +1.
How badly will Spain and Portugal want to avoide the Russia side? Or are the wins against Egypt and the Saudis rather meaningless.
Russia has shored up its place in the 16 whereas some of the traditional powerhouses are off to a much shakier start.
Spain all but locks it up. Portugal only vulnerable to a loss to Iran now.
Model update. In order of likeliness to progress: Russia (100%) England (95%) Belgium (94%) France (88%) Brazil (86%) Spain (85%) Portugal (77%) Argentina (73%) Switzerland (67%) Germany (59%)

The second round of group matches should start sorting the teams out. If Argentina and Switzerland win against Croatia and Serbia, the probability of all these ten teams going through to the last sixteen will increase - unless of course there is a major upset in one or more of the other games.
1.13 (-0.17 on RUS win)
Subtle changes, as Russia locks up a final 16 position.
Model update.
Changes overnight as England and Belgium join Russia as "near certainties" to make the round of 16.

All ten teams have played their first matches, and my initial impression is that the competition is more equal than I expected, with none of the top tier teams (Brazil, Germany, Spain) winning their first games.

Using the 538 model (https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2018-world-cup-predictions/) ... as I presume most others are here.

Updated model. Obviously a number of teams dropping points in their opening games has meant that fewer are expected to progress. In order of likeliness: Russia (94%) Brazil (87%) France (87%) England (87%) Spain (84%) Belgium (84%) Portugal (79%) Argentina (74%) Switzerland 66%) Germany (65%)
Still around 1.53
Russian (strictly legal) - influence on outcomes? Environment can influence matches:

Thanks @Khalid for pointing to 538's live model that seems to update every minute. I update my numbers a bit in their direction, comparing my initial predictions with their probabilities that individual teams would succeed beyond the group stage.
Swiss and now Argentina seem to be the most likely candidates.
Swiss now seem the most likely to fail, however the Swiss traditionally give up few goals and sometimes advance on 3 points from draws.

Russia wins 5:0 in opening match --> medium update that russia will make it to the next stage --> taking some probability mass from 3 or more teams not making it closer to only 1 or 2 groups not making it.
Model update.

Saudi gift of 5 goals, 3 late, to WC host and OPEC teammate Russia makes Russia progression to second round more likely. Might get to second round with only a tie against Egypt on goal deferential. Suspect the Saudis will play tougher against Egypt.
Correcting forecast error
https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2018-world-cup-predictions/

If group performance were predicted by FIFA world ranking alone, all teams but Russia would go through to the knock outs. There is still a high level of uncertainty, as strong teams will under perform and underdogs will overcome. Additionally, there are many groups where there are strong competitors close to these teams in FIFA ranking. For instance, England are 13th and Group G rivals Tunisia are 14th. At this stage, I have based my forecast on the FIFA rankings, accounting for uncertainty.
Update to previous model.
These are all the favorites. The odds of one not getting to the round of 16 are already low, but the odds of at least one are considerable. Something always goes wrong along the way.

Slightly increasing odds on 2. Argentina loses top goalkeeper. In addition it seems one injury to Messi may end Argentinian WC. http://www.sportingnews.com/soccer/news/romero-confirms-he-will-stay-at-man-united/1tz1mj9lih5t91jvrag9p75tsh
Flattening out the probabilities compared to my initial guesstimate yesterday of 5/45/40/10/0.

Model update as for Winner forecast. Most likely to progress, in order: Brazil (91%) Germany (91%) Spain (87%) Russia (87%) England (85%) Belgium (83%) Argentina (81%) France (78%) Portugal (77%) Switzerland (58%)

Betting markets make Brazil (2/17), France (1/10), Germany (1/7), Spain (1/10) and Belgium (1/10) clear odds-on favorites to win their groups and reach the last 16. Other odds on favorites to reach the last 16 are England (1/6) and Portugal (1/3), both expected to come second in their groups.

Giving England a 10% chance, based on long shot Tunesia and Enland's uncertain defence. Giving Russia a 30% chance, having played no qualifying marches as tournament host, offset with home advantage and minimal travel schedule, but Egypt is the only competition for the number 2 spot in Group "A". Giving France a20% chance due to strong competition from both Peru and Denmark in Group "C". Giving Spain a 20% chance, as Portugal may be the Group favorite, and Morocco and Iran are adequate defensively. Swiss get a 67% chance, Brazil is clear favorite in the Group and Costa Rica and Serbia have a chance. Everyone else should easily move on. Total odds seem to be around 1.5 failures for second round, increasing the odds slightly due to many wildcards: injuries, red & yellow cards, penalty kicks, and the opportunity for a Group leader to throw the last match to keep a competitor out of the second round.

there are always a couple of "sure" teams who underperform. I consider Russia and Switzerland not to have an easy road to go through. Then, there might always be a surprise of a "big" team not going through.
According to the betting odds five of these have about 66% of going through, 2 a bit better than 50%, with three others considerably behind: Portugal, Russia and Switzerland.
WoC PoT.

Argentina: 5th in world ranking, in group D with Iceland, Croatia and Nigeria (22th, 18th, 47th) --> 90% chance to preceed Belgium: 3rd in world ranking, in group G with Panama, Tunisia and England (55th, 14th, 13th) --> 90% Brazil: 2nd in world ranking, in group E with Switzerland, Costa Rica and Serbia (6th, 25th, 35th) --> 90% England: 13th in world ranking, in group G with Belgium, Panama and Tunisia (3rd, 55th, 14th) --> 50% France: 7th in world ranking, in group C with Australia, Peru and Denmark (40th, 11th, 12th) --> 50% Germany: 1st in world ranking, in group F with Mexico, Sweden and South Korea (15th, 23rd, 61st) --> 98% Portugal: 4th in world ranking, in group with Spain, Morocco and Iran (8th, 42nd, 36th) --> 90% Russia: 66th on the Fifa World Ranking, but also in a weak group with Saudi Arabia, Uruguay and Egypt, + host bonus --> ~50% to proceed Spain: 8th in world ranking, in group with Portugal, Morocco and Iran (4th, 42nd, 36th) --> 90% Switzerland: 6ths in world ranking, in group E with Brazil, Costa Rica and Serbia (2nd, 25th, 35th) --> 80%

Quite a number very comfortable to qualify (POR,SPA,ARG,BRA,SWI,GER). FRA exit unlikely, as would require both Peru and Denmark to outperform expectations, but an outside possibility. Either ENG or BEL could be overcome by Tunisia; unlikely, but most plausible way for one if the main 9 listed not to make it. Russia shouldn’t be good enough to get out of group, but home advantage might allow them to scrape through (albeit with a low probability).
